Saving R Markdown files

Getting set up

R markdown files are saved in the xxx directory

Knit to HTML

Click the Knit button in the top menu (below file tabs) to create an HTML file. If successful, you should see a preview of your HTML document in the right pane. If unsuccessful, you will need to correct errors in the identified lines/chunks of code so that your file can run successfully from start to finish.

In the R Studio viewer pane, click the “Show in New Window ” button to view the page in your browser.


Push to Github


Make understandable code

How big should each chunk be?

Good writing involves structuring sentences logically to build an argument. In the same way, chunks can be used to structure lines of code to build an analysis or a plot.

Paragraphs each describe one idea or argument. Chunks work like paragraphs - each chunk should describe one task or provide one type of output.

Adding brief summaries

For others to understand what your code does and why you made the choices you did, it’s good to include brief summaries or your logic or what each line of your code does.

Using code chunks

Sometimes you may wish to show the code you used to do a task without actually running it. Most often, this is because a code or function takes a long time to run, and you may have saved local files to increase the speed of your workflow.

For others who read your code, however, it is essential that they know where every file comes from - nothing is more frustrating than wondering where to access data or a file that you need to run someone else’s code.

This is where you can use ‘eval’ and ‘echo’ in your chunk headers to control what code and results are knitted to your HTML file.

For example, avoid running a chunk of code but still show the code:

ala_counts(group_by = "phylum")
